  _d("ara-metua-coral-road","Ara Metua Ancient Coral Road","Rarotonga","1,000-Year-Old Stone Road","cook+islands,ara+metua,ancient+road,coral+stone,historic,maori",
    "A 1,000-year-old coral-paved road running through Rarotonga's interior — one of the finest surviving examples of ancient Polynesian infrastructure, linking marae temple platforms.",
    "The Ara Metua is a raised coral-stone road dating from approximately 1000 CE, running parallel to the coastal road through the island's interior jungle and connecting the most important ancient marae. The coral blocks were fitted without mortar in a construction technique mastered by ancient Polynesian engineers.\n\nSections of the road remain intact and walkable, with native tree ferns and tropical plants growing through and over the ancient stones — a living ruin of haunting beauty.",
    {"Age":"~1,000 years (built c. 1000 CE)","Material":"Raised coral-stone blocks, unmortared","Function":"Linked ancient marae temple platforms","Condition":"Partially intact; sections walkable","Location":"Parallel to coastal road in interior"},
    "Year-round (self-guided access)","Free","21.2500° S, 159.7667° W",
    "Walk the Ara Metua section near Ngatangiia village on a cloudy morning — the filtered jungle light on ancient coral stone, with ferns growing through the paving, is one of the Pacific's most atmospheric heritage walks.")
